definition: "Vitamin B6 is a family of six related compounds (pyridoxine, pyridoxal, pyridoxamine, and their 5'-phosphate forms) that are collectively converted in the body to pyridoxal-5'-phosphate (PLP) — the active coenzyme form. PLP functions as a coenzyme in over 100 enzymatic reactions, predominantly involving amino acid metabolism: transamination, decarboxylation, racemization, and elimination reactions that produce or transform amino acids, neurotransmitters, and metabolic intermediates. Key PLP-dependent processes include synthesis of serotonin (from tryptophan), dopamine and norepinephrine (from tyrosine), GABA (from glutamate), histamine, and the porphyrin ring required for hemoglobin production. PLP is also a critical cofactor in the transsulfuration pathway that converts homocysteine to cystathionine — making B6 one of three vitamins (alongside B12 and folate) essential for homocysteine clearance. The standard blood test for B6 measures serum or plasma PLP, the active coenzyme form, which best reflects functional vitamin B6 status."
why_it_matters: "Vitamin B6 deficiency is more common than most people assume — estimated to affect 10–25% of the US population based on dietary intake surveys, with higher rates in older adults, people taking certain medications (notably oral contraceptives and isoniazid), individuals with chronic inflammation (which accelerates PLP catabolism), and those with inflammatory bowel disease or alcohol use disorders. The functional consequences of suboptimal B6 span three major domains. Neurologically: PLP is required to synthesize serotonin, dopamine, and GABA — the primary mood-regulating neurotransmitters. Suboptimal B6 is associated with depression, anxiety, cognitive decline, and peripheral neuropathy. Cardiovascularly: PLP is required for homocysteine clearance via the transsulfuration pathway; B6 deficiency elevates homocysteine, raising cardiovascular risk. Hematologically: PLP is required for heme synthesis; B6 deficiency produces a sideroblastic anemia pattern where iron accumulates in bone marrow precursors but cannot be incorporated into hemoglobin. The combination of neurotransmitter synthesis, homocysteine metabolism, and heme production makes B6 one of the most metabolically central B vitamins."

standard_range: "Serum PLP: 5–50 ng/mL (reference ranges vary by laboratory)"
